</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,152,680]" pageId="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,275,499,525]" pageId="17">Notes.</emphasis>
This species belongs to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Staeger" authorityYear="1840" box="[638,846,500,525]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Boletina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sciarina">
<emphasis box="[638,846,500,525]" italics="true" pageId="17">Boletina sciarina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, which also includes the other Sardinian species except 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1818" box="[333,452,538,563]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">
<emphasis box="[333,452,538,563]" italics="true" pageId="17">B. basalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and many others in the Palaearctic fauna. These are characterised by absence of setae on the laterotergite and the structure of the male genitalia including an undivided gonostylus. Within this group it resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dziedzicki" authorityYear="1885" box="[391,509,616,641]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Boletina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gripha">
<emphasis box="[391,509,616,641]" italics="true" pageId="17">B. gripha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and a few other species in having partly darkened coxae and differs from previously known species in the form of the gonocoxites and gonostylus.
</paragraph>
